            Comprehensive Prevention Strategies
          </h2>
          <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            Effective workplace substance abuse prevention goes beyond simply implementing a drug testing program. 
            A comprehensive approach includes:
          </p>
  
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
            1. Clear, Supportive Policies
          </h3>
          <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
            Develop and communicate substance abuse policies that balance deterrence with support:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Define prohibited behaviors and substances clearly
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Outline the consequences of policy violations
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Emphasize that the company's primary concern is employee wellbeing
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Detail the support resources available to employees
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Include procedures that respect privacy and dignity
            </li>
          </ul>
  
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
            2. Education and Awareness Programs
          </h3>
          <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
            Knowledge is a powerful prevention tool. Provide education on:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              The health and safety risks associated with substance abuse
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              How to recognize signs of substance abuse in oneself and others
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              The impact of substance use on work performance and safety
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Available resources for seeking help
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Dispelling myths and reducing stigma around addiction and treatment
            </li>
          </ul>
  
          <!-- Important Note Section -->
          <div
            class="my-8 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-6 py-2 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm"
          >
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-yellow-800 mb-2">Important Note</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Educational programs are most effective when they're ongoing rather than one-time events. 
              Consider incorporating substance abuse awareness into regular safety meetings, new employee 
              orientation, and periodic refresher trainings.
            </p>
          </div>
  
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
            3. Employee Assistance Programs (EAPs)
          </h3>
          <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
            EAPs are one of the most valuable tools employers can offer:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Provide confidential assessment, counseling, and referral services
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Address not only substance abuse but also underlying issues like stress, mental health concerns, 
              and work-life balance
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Regularly promote EAP services to reduce stigma and encourage utilization
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              Ensure confidentiality to build trust in the program
            </li>
          </ul>
  
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
            4. Supportive Work Environment
          </h3>
          <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
            The workplace culture itself can either contribute to or help prevent substance abuse:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Address workplace stressors</strong> - 
              High stress is a risk factor for substance abuse
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Promote work-life balance</strong> - 
              Excessive work demands can lead to unhealthy coping mechanisms
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Provide mental health resources</strong> - 
              Mental health and substance use issues often co-occur
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Develop a positive social climate</strong> - 
              Strong workplace relationships provide natural support systems
            </li>
            <li class="leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Examine workplace norms around alcohol</strong> - 
              Evaluate whether company events and culture normalize excessive drinking
            </li>
          </ul>
  
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
            5. Supervisor Training
          </h3>
